"Following the eruption of the Grímsvötn volcano in Iceland, significant disruptions were observed in air travel, particularly affecting routes between Europe and North America. Gander Airport, located on the eastern tip of Newfoundland, played a crucial role as a stopover point for transatlantic flights. However, by the 1970s, the importance of Gander began to wane due to the rise of larger aircraft capable of longer direct flights. Nevertheless, Gander remained an important air traffic control hub, especially for oceanic flights. The situation was further complicated by the 9/11 terrorist attacks in 2001, when Gander Airport redirected all westbound North Atlantic air traffic, landing 40 planes. In the years leading up to the eruption, several notable incidents involving air accidents and near-misses were recorded, such as those listed in the NTSB reports from the 1970s and 1990s. These events underscored the challenges faced by air traffic controllers and the need for continuous improvement in safety protocols. As the ash cloud from the Grímsvötn eruption spread, numerous flights were grounded, and thousands of passengers were left stranded. To provide guidance to affected travelers, the Irish Aviation Authority released a list of canceled flights to and from Irish airports, which included cancellations to and from Göteborg Landvetter Airport in Sweden. Over the course of the week, the situation evolved, with many flights resuming operation as the ash cloud dissipated. Notably, flights from Scotland and Northern Ireland experienced significant disruptions, with numerous cancellations reported. By the end of the week, the majority of flights had resumed normal operations, though some airlines continued to experience delays and cancellations due to lingering concerns about ash cloud contamination."

trgt_first: Precipitation is low compared to much of East Tennessee, averaging 41.0 inches (1,040 mm) annually, and reaches a low during autumn. The rainiest calendar day on record is October 16, 1964, when 3.65 inches (93 mm) of rain fell; monthly precipitation has ranged from 0.02 inches (0.51 mm) in October 2002 to 12.70 inches (323 mm) in July 2012.
mgt: Bristol, Tennessee, averages 12 inches (300 mm) of snow per year, less than the state average. The most snowfall in one day was 12 inches on January 31, 1999. On November 21, 1952, 14 inches fell. The most snow in one month was 29 inches in January 1959, a significant winter storm. This contrasts with the 1959–60 winter, where only 4 inches were recorded, unusually low for the region.

section_title: == Loss of territory and activity as raiding force ==
trgt: IS attacks continue in all parts of Libya. In operating as mobile raiders, the Islamic State militants attempt to prevent the restoration of state authority throughout Libya, thereby maintaining a chaotic situation in which they could attempt a comeback in the future. The IS central command also regards its forces' continued presence in Libya as important due to the area being a useful springboard for terrorist attacks on Europe and for an expansion into and connection with Sub-Saharan Africa.
trgt_first: Over a course of ten days in 2019, from September 19 to 29, AFRICOM claimed airstrikes that they carried out on the Islamic State in southwestern Libya on four separate occasions left 43 militants dead. As of 2020, the IS forces in Libya mostly operate as moving insurgencies. Instead of trying to hold territory, they temporarily occupying areas and raid them, launch attacks on security posts, and generally cause instability.
mgt: Despite these setbacks, IS militants continue sporadic attacks across Libya, operating as raiding forces to prevent the restoration of state authority and maintain a fragmented status quo. They aim to expand into undergoverned regions, particularly in the central and southern parts of the country, to connect with other extremist groups and maintain a strategic base for terrorist activities.

Among the latter, such souls as have departed with faith but "without having had time to bring forth fruits worthy of repentance ... may be aided towards the attainment of a blessed resurrection [at the end of time] by prayers offered in their behalf, especially those offered in union with the oblation of the bloodless sacrifice of the Body and Blood of Christ, and by works of mercy done in faith for their memory."
trgt_first: The Eastern Orthodox Church holds that it is necessary to believe in this intermediate after-death state in which souls are perfected and brought to full divinization, a process of growth rather than of punishment, which some Orthodox have called purgatory. Eastern Orthodox theology does not generally describe the situation of the dead as involving suffering or fire, although it nevertheless describes it as a "direful condition".
mgt: The Eastern Orthodox Church holds that it is necessary to believe in this intermediate after-death state in which souls are perfected and brought to full divinization, a process of growth rather than punishment, which some Orthodox have called purgatory. The souls of the righteous dead experience a state of comfort, often referred to as the "Bosom of Abraham," while the wicked souls endure torment. Souls that have departed with faith but without having had time to bring forth fruits worthy of repentance can be aided through prayers and works of mercy. These include liturgies and deeds of charity, which can provide relief from their suffering. The ultimate goal for these souls is rest in a place of brightness, where all sickness, sighing, and sorrow have fled away.

This also causes re-bonding of the matrix-matrix as well as matrix-fiber essentially improving the tensile strength as well as dynamic mechanical properties by creating a much denser structure.
trgt_first: For this specific case, the workpiece is fabricated with Fused Deposition Modelling (FDM), an additive manufacturing method. Typically, all the additively manufactured components have defects throughout their matrix, viz. gas porosity, gap between deposited layers, inconsistent lamination of the deposited layers and low adhesion among layers. All of the aforementioned terms have related or unrelated reasons of formation which can be studied in depth, but are beyond scope of this summary.
mgt:

**Continuation:**

Tensile properties of the newly polished fiber and matrix at the workpiece surface are significantly enhanced due to the precise control of the laser beam. The failure sources or origins of damage induced in the composite during the laser polishing process include localized thermal stresses and microstructural changes within the material. These localized thermal stresses can initiate cracks or other defects, which may propagate and affect the overall tensile strength of the composite.

The failure behavior of the composite can be altered by the degree of laser power and the scanning speed, which dictate the extent of surface melting and the subsequent cooling and solidification process. During laser polishing, the surface material undergoes a series of transformations, including partial melting and remelting, leading to a homogenization of the microstructure and a reduction in surface roughness.

When the melted surface material flows from the peaks to the unfilled valleys, it effectively fills in any voids or defects present in the surface, thereby removing the original damage and creating a smoother, more uniform surface. This re-bonding process enhances the adhesion between the matrix and fibers, as well as between matrix particles, leading to improved tensile strength and dynamic mechanical properties.

The re-bonding of the matrix-matrix and matrix-fiber interfaces results in a more cohesive composite structure, which can withstand higher tensile loads without failure. This improvement in tensile strength and dynamic mechanical properties is achieved through the elimination of surface defects and the creation of a more uniform microstructure. As a result, the overall performance and durability of the composite material are significantly enhanced, making it more suitable for demanding applications.

Dave Frishberg was renowned for his witty and sophisticated songwriting, often blending humor with poignant melodies. He was celebrated for his jazz hits such as "Peel Me a Grape," "Blizzard of Lies," and "My Attorney Bernie," which showcased his knack for clever wordplay and inventive melodies. His performances and recordings garnered critical acclaim and two Grammy nominations for The Dave Frishberg Songbooks on Omnisound. Frishberg passed away on October 24, 2023, at the age of 88, leaving behind a legacy of insightful and entertaining musical works.

trgt: Article 4 of the Mandate provided for "the recognition of an appropriate Jewish agency as a public body for the purpose of advising and co-operating with the Administration of Palestine in such economic, social and other matters as may affect the establishment of the Jewish National Home and the interests of the Jewish population of Palestine." The ZO leaders had contributed to the drafting of the Mandate. In November 1921, the Zionist Commission became the Palestine Zionist Executive and was designated as the Jewish agency for Palestine for the purpose of Article 4 of the Palestine Mandate.
trgt_first: On 25 April 1920, the Principal Allied Powers agreed at the San Remo conference to allocate the Ottoman territories to the victorious powers and assigned Palestine, Transjordan and Iraq as Mandates to Britain, with the Balfour Declaration being incorporated into the Palestine Mandate. The League of Nations formally approved these mandates in 1922.
mgt: On 25 April 1920, the Principal Allied Powers agreed at the San Remo conference to allocate the Ottoman territories to the victorious powers and assigned Palestine, Transjordan, and Iraq as Mandates to Britain, with the Balfour Declaration being incorporated into the Palestine Mandate. Article 4 provided for a Jewish agency to be responsible for the development of Jewish settlements. The mandate was drafted with input from various parties, including the Zionist Organization. In November 1921, the Zionist Commission became the Palestine Zionist Executive, which was designated as the Jewish Agency for the purpose of Article 4. According to the mandate, the Palestine Zionist Executive was to assist in the development of Jewish agriculture, forestry, and industry in Palestine.

trgt: A review by Wyndham Wallace for the BBC said, "Much of Sonnamble's work is improvised, but there's an art to what they do: Curran’s homemade software seems able to reduce every note down to its even smaller constituent parts and then sieve out what suits their goal. The sound is therefore strangely granular, with the opening notes of Aphelion I spreading out and blurring at the edges until they distort and flutter into tiny sounds of their own. It's like moving one's face ever closer to a TV screen, with the picture slowly reduced from an overall pattern to a mass of pixels. What is experienced isn't identifiable in any standard sense, but is nonetheless fascinating."
trgt_first: Sonnamble's second album. Blindlight, was released in 2011 on Forwind. "Again the focus is on Marsh's lap steel guitar, whose drones, chords and twangs are coaxed into expansive ambient fuzziness or atomised into grains of noise by Curran's home-cooked software patches. But there's a spareness and a more pronounced spikiness to the music this time round; it's still immersive stuff, but more edgy...".
mgt: The BBC Review, written by Wyndham Wallace in 2011, describes Sonnamble's approach as macrocosmic. Curran's homemade software reduces each note to its smallest components, creating a granular sound. Wallace characterizes the album as "dull and uninspired," with the opening notes of Aphelion I spreading and distorting into tiny sounds. Listening to Sonnamble's music is likened to moving closer to a TV screen, where the picture becomes a mass of pixels, identifiable yet fascinating in its detail.

section_title: == Peg Goldberg and the Kanakaria mosaics ==
trgt: These mosaics have fallen into destruction because of the damage that they experienced through the process of removal from the church, shipping around the world, and during the restoration work that Goldberg commissioned. It is unlikely that these mosaics will ever be reinstalled in their original home, even if there are changes in the political situation on Cyprus, because they would most likely not make it through the re-installation process in the state that they are currently in.
trgt_first: The mosaic pieces that were involved in the Kanakaria case have four different religious images. They depict Jesus as a young boy, the archangel Michael, Matthew and James; the final two are images of apostles from the 1st century. The mosaics were named after the Church in which they were placed originally around 530.
mgt: The destruction and damage were largely due to theft by Aydin Dikmen in the 1970s, and the subsequent sale of the pieces to various collectors. Restoration was commissioned by the Cyprus Byzantine Museum. Reinstallation is possible but faces challenges; the condition of the fragments is uncertain. The mosaics originally adorned the Church of the Panagia Kanakaria in Lythrankomi. Concerns include the authenticity and quality of the reassembled pieces. Successful reinstallation depends on the availability of all fragments and funding for conservation efforts.

trgt: Many animals evolved including mammoths, giant ground sloths, dire wolves, saber-toothed cats, and most famously Homo sapiens. 100,000 years ago marked the end of one of the worst droughts in Africa, and led to the expansion of primitive humans. As the Pleistocene drew to a close, a major extinction wiped out much of the world's megafauna, including some of the hominid species, such as Neanderthals. All the continents were affected, but Africa to a lesser extent. It still retains many large animals, such as hippos.
trgt_first: The Pleistocene lasted from 2.58 million to 11,700 years ago. This epoch was marked by ice ages as a result of the cooling trend that started in the Mid-Eocene. There were at least four separate glaciation periods marked by the advance of ice caps as far south as 40° N in mountainous areas. Meanwhile, Africa experienced a trend of desiccation which resulted in the creation of the Sahara, Namib, and Kalahari deserts.
mgt: The Quaternary, which began 2.58 million years ago and continues today, saw the evolution of Homo sapiens. Around 11,700 years ago, a severe drought ended in Africa, leading to famine and significant loss of life. As the Pleistocene drew to a close, a major extinction event decimated large mammal populations, particularly in North and South America and Australia, while Africa was less affected. This event, centered around 11,000 years before present, wiped out many genera of large mammals, including mammoths, mastodons, and ground sloths in North America. Africa retained its large mammals, which had coexisted with humans for millennia.

trgt: Only the strongest electrophiles are able to do this, and these are usually dications or, more rarely, monocations, since high electrophilicity is accompanied by a substantial lack of electrons. In contrast, it is impossible for nucleophiles, which provide electrons for bond formation, to bind a noble gas strongly, because noble gases have negative electron affinities. Only weak interactions (ion- induced dipole and dispersion) are usually present, and do not result in a stable bond at room temperature.
trgt_first: Later, the term superelectrophilic was also frequently applied in gas phase studies to highly reactive dications that can bind noble gases at room temperature. Noble gases are generally considered to be particularly inert - in order to form a stable bond with a noble gas atom, a pair of electrons must be abstracted from it.
mgt: The term superelectrophilic was further refined to describe highly reactive dications or monocations, typically carrying a positive charge, capable of binding noble gases at room temperature. These strong electrophiles, often metal-containing cations, outcompete nucleophiles due to their high electron affinity and ability to abstract electron density from noble gases. Noble gases have negative electron affinities, making them reluctant to form stable bonds with nucleophiles. Instead, nucleophiles interact weakly with noble gases, resulting in transient complexes that are not stable at room temperature.

trgt: Claws are pointed at their ends and are composed of two layers: a thick, deep layer and a superficial, hardened layer which serves a protective function. The underlying bone is a virtual mold of the overlying horny structure and therefore has the same shape as the claw or nail. Compared to claws, nails are flat, less curved, and do not extend far beyond the tip of the digits. The ends of the nails usually consist only of the "superficial", hardened layer and are not pointed like claws.
trgt_first: In contrast to nails, claws are typically curved ventrally (downwards in animals) and compressed sideways. They serve a multitude of functions—including climbing, digging, and fighting—and have undergone numerous adaptive changes in different animal taxa.
mgt: In primates, claws are less common, typically found only on the second toe (hallux). Unlike claws, which are composed of multiple layers of keratin and have a hard, superficial layer over an underlying bone, nails are generally flat and have a single layer of keratin. Claws are more curved and laterally compressed compared to the relatively straight and thinner nails, which usually end in a free edge rather than a point.

All of Spanish West Florida west of the Perdido River, including the important port of Mobile, was occupied by the Americans in 1813, but the Treaty of Ghent did not force the Americans to leave this section of West Florida. The treaty made no changes to the prewar boundaries on the U.S.-Canada border.
trgt_first: The treaty released all prisoners and restored all captured lands and ships between the United States and Britain (Mobile and Spanish West Florida territory west of the Perdido River were not returned to Spain, who allied with Britain and the Red Stick Creeks in the War of 1812, by the United States).
mgt: The treaty released all prisoners and restored all captured lands and ships between the United States and Britain. It returned approximately 5 million acres of treaty-guaranteed land to Indigenous nations, including lands near Lakes Michigan and Superior. Americans retained control of Detroit, Mackinac Island, and other territories, while British forces withdrew from the Maine coast and Fort Mackinac. The treaty did not specify the return of Spanish West Florida west of the Perdido River but confirmed the U.S. occupation of the area. No changes were made to the prewar boundaries on the U.S.-Canada border.

section_title: == US and USSR military and economic issues ==
trgt: This buildup was accelerated by the Reagan administration, which increased the military spending from 5.3 percent of GNP in 1981 to 6.5 percent in 1986, the largest peacetime defense buildup in United States history. The American-Soviet tensions present during 1983 was defined by some as the start of "Cold War II". Whilst in retrospective this phase of the Cold War was generally defined as a "war of words", the Soviet's "peace offensive" was largely rejected by the West.
trgt_first: By the early 1980s, the USSR had built up a military arsenal and army surpassing that of the United States. Soon after the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, president Carter began massively building up the United States military.
mgt:
No other instructions. 

Continuation:

By the early 1980s, the USSR had built up a military arsenal and army surpassing that of the United States. Soon after the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, President Reagan accelerated the military buildup, increasing military spending from 5.3% to 6% of GDP between 1981 and 1986, reaching $1,500 billion. This era marked a significant escalation in the Cold War, characterized by heightened tensions and arms races. Some defined the American-Soviet tensions during 1983 as a period of "great tension," while others viewed it as a time of "frightening situations." Despite this, the West, including the U.S., responded to the Soviet "peace offensive" with skepticism, seeing it as a strategic maneuver rather than a genuine shift in policy.

trgt: For nearly 50 years, the houses concealed entrances to the third largest military facility in Yugoslavia (after the underground Željava Air Base near Bihać and the Lora naval facility in Split, Croatia). The houses consist of a control residence, a building containing secure communication links, and a facility for technical support personnel. Along a corridor located in the first house, three 1.2-meter-thick metal doors protect a tunnel leading to the heart of the shelter, which is 280 meters deep and 202 meters long.
trgt_first: Visible from the outside of the complex are three nondescript houses, not marked on any map, in an isolated natural setting located along the Neretva River.
mgt:
What is the function of the second house?

Continuation:
Construction of the houses began in 1960, concealing entrances to the military facility for approximately 20 years. The facility, known as Armijska Ratna Komanda D-0, was the largest military command center in Yugoslavia, ranking third in size. The two larger facilities were the General Staff Headquarters and the Air Force Command Center. The houses consisted of a main living area, bedrooms, and a secret compartment designed to house the military command center. In the first house, along a corridor, was a hidden entrance to the underground tunnel system leading to the command center. The second house served as a secondary command post, providing backup control in case of emergencies or enemy attacks.

trgt_first: The social season played a role in the political life of the country: the members of the two Houses of Parliament were almost all participants in the season. But the Season also provided an opportunity for the children of marriageable age of the nobility and gentry to be launched into society.
mgt: Debutantes, typically from noble and gentry families, were formally introduced into society by presentation to the monarch at royal court events such as Queen Charlotte's Ball. The practice was abolished by Queen Elizabeth II in 1958, following Prince Philip's insistence. Queen Charlotte's Ball ceased functioning in 1976, but was later relaunched under the patronage of the Duke of Somerset. In the relaunched event, debutantes curtsy to an 8-foot cake on Queen Charlotte's birthday.

trgt: Jencks makes the point that Post-Modernism (like Modernism) varies for each field of art, and that for architecture it is not just a reaction to Modernism but what he terms double coding: "Double Coding: the combination of Modern techniques with something else (usually traditional building) in order for architecture to communicate with the public and a concerned minority, usually other architects." In their book, "Revisiting Postmodernism", Terry Farrell and Adam Furman argue that postmodernism brought a more joyous and sensual experience to the culture, particularly in architecture.
trgt_first: The intellectual scholarship regarding postmodernism and architecture is closely linked with the writings of critic-turned-architect Charles Jencks, beginning with lectures in the early 1970s and his essay "The Rise of Post Modern Architecture" from 1975. His magnum opus, however, is the book The Language of Post-Modern Architecture, first published in 1977, and since running to seven editions.
mgt: The intellectual scholarship regarding postmodernism and architecture is closely linked with the writings of critic-turned-architect Charles Jencks, beginning with lectures in the early 1970s and his essay "The Rise of Post Modern Architecture" from 1975. Jencks noted that postmodernism varies for each field of art, describing it in architecture as a critique of Modernism's dogmatism. He coined the term "double coding" to describe the combination of modern techniques with traditional or historical styles. Jencks argues that double coding appeals to both professionals and the general public. In their book "Revisiting Postmodernism," Sir Terry Farrell and Adam Nathaniel Furman argue that postmodernism brought a more joyous and sensual approach to architecture, particularly noting its impact on the cultural landscape. They claim postmodernism provided a richer, more engaging experience in architecture.

mgt: After the release of "There's a Riot Goin' On," a post-concert brawl erupted between Graham's and Sly's entourages, triggered by Bubba Banks and Eddie Chin's absurd claim that Graham had hired a hit man to kill Sly. Graham and his wife escaped through a hotel window and were driven to safety by Pat Rizzo. Following this incident, Graham left the Family Stone and formed Grand Central Station. trgt_first: Music critic Tom Ewing, writing for Freaky Trigger, later gave the song a 9/10 in a series where he individually reviews every UK number one single ever, saying it mixes the Doctor Who theme tune "with the pop sounds of 1974, the year of glam rock and Davros, scarves on the Rollers and scarves on the new Doctor, glitterbeat and “Blockbuster” airhorns.
mgt: "Doctorin' the Tardis" is often compared to a companion piece to the original "Doctor Who" theme, capturing the spirit of the 1970s. It beckons listeners onto the dancefloor, reminiscent of the era's vibrant nightlife. Unlike some modern hits, it does not invite boy gangs of yobs and nerds to its party. In a line of descent from "Hoots Mon" and "Mouldy Old Dough," both described as novelty monster songs, "Doctorin' the Tardis" captures the essence of the time more truly than many serious songs. While not quite reaching the quality of "Theme From S'Express," it remains a charming and nostalgic tribute to the era.

trgt: : 158 At the aft end of the Starship spacecraft are six Raptor engines, three of which are designed for operation in the lower atmosphere, and the other three Raptor Vacuum engines are optimized to operate in the vacuum of space. A set of reaction control thrusters mounted at the spacecraft's exterior control the spacecraft's attitude while in space.
trgt_first: Starship has a total propellant capacity of 1,200 t (2,600,000 lb), divided into main tanks and header tanks. The header tanks are better insulated due to their position and are reserved for use to flip and land the spacecraft following reentry. About 130 L (34 US gal) of hydraulic fluid is used for the spacecraft's operations.
mgt: Starship is powered by six Raptor engines, with three for sea-level operation and three Raptor Vacuum engines for space. These engines provide thrust for orbit and deep space missions. Reaction control thrusters, mounted around the circumference, manage the spacecraft's attitude and translation in space, operating efficiently in the vacuum of space.

Severe sanctions included the death penalty for sodomy until 1861, followed by mandatory 10-year prison sentences until 1885, when all male homosexual acts became illegal. Edleston, a Cambridge chorister, gave Byron a carnelian ring, which inspired Byron's poem "The Cornelian."

Ford added significant depth to our understanding of Leeuwenhoek's work, arguing that Leeuwenhoek was not merely an amateur but a diligent experimenter. Ford's opinion challenged the prevailing view that Leeuwenhoek was an outsider or an amateur. The popular perception was that Leeuwenhoek's work was limited and lacked rigor. However, the survival of his specimens and the high quality of his work contradicted this view. Leeuwenhoek was willing to oppose the concept of spontaneous generation and construct experimental models to support his views. His meticulous procedures and observations laid the groundwork for future scientific discoveries.

trgt: Another possible explanation, instead of intra-species aggression, for this sexual dimorphism may be that it is an adaption for a sexual division of labor with males doing the hunting. However, the hunting theory may have difficulty explaining differences regarding features such as stronger protective skeleton, beards (not helpful in hunting, but they increase the perceived size of the jaws and perceived dominance, which may be helpful in intra-species male competition), and greater male ability at interception (greater targeting ability can be explained by hunting).
trgt_first: In species that have high levels of male physical competition and aggression over females, males tend to be larger and stronger than females. Humans have modest general body sexual dimorphism on characteristics such as height and body mass. However, this may understate the sexual dimorphism regarding characteristics related to aggression since females have large fat stores. The sex differences are greater for muscle mass and especially for upper body muscle mass. Men's skeleton, especially in the vulnerable face, is more robust.
mgt: One alternative explanation for facial sexual dimorphism is sexual selection through inter-sexual choice rather than intra-sexual aggression. Males' larger lower faces and jaws may not aid in hunting but instead enhance perceived dominance. Beards, which increase the appearance of jaw size, may help in male-male competition for mates. This aligns with the role of hunting in developing upper body strength, a specific ability that can be advantageous in such competitions.

trgt: While a popular local Yemenite Jewish preacher called on Jews to choose martyrdom, Maimonides sent what is known by the name Iggeret Teman ("Epistle to Yemen"), requesting that they remain faithful to their religion, but if at all possible, not to cast affronts before their antagonists. The persecution ended in 1173 with the defeat of Ibn Mahdi and conquest of Yemen by Turan-Shah, the brother of Saladin, and they were allowed to return to their faith. According to two Genizah documents, the Ayyubid ruler of Yemen, al-Malik al-Mu'izz al-Ismail (reigned 1197—1202) attempted to force the Jews of Aden to convert. The second document details the relief of Jewish community after his murder and those who had been forced to convert reverted to Judaism.
trgt_first: Yemenite Jews also experienced violent persecution at times. In the late 1160s, the Yemenite ruler 'Abd-al-Nabī ibn Mahdi gave Jews a choice of conversion to Islam or martyrdom. Mahdi also imposed his beliefs upon the Muslims besides the Jews. This led to a revival of Jewish messianism, but also led to mass-conversion.
mgt: In the late 1160s, the Yemenite ruler 'Abd-al-Nabī ibn Mahdi forced Jews to choose between conversion or martyrdom, leading to mass conversions. This sparked a revival of Jewish messianism, with preachers like Rabbi Jacob ben Nathanael al-Fayyumi urging Jews to resist. In response, Maimonides wrote the Iggeret Teman, advising the Jews of Yemen on how to preserve their faith. Saladin, with his brother Turan Shah's military support, defeated Ibn Mahdi in 1174, ending persecution and allowing Jews to return to their faith. The Ayyubid ruler of Yemen, Saladin, then attempted to force the Jews of Aden to convert, but their community thrived under his rule.

trgt: However, because the trochlea is wider in front than at the back (approximately 5–6 mm) the stability in the joint vary with the position of the foot: with the foot dorsiflexed (toes pulled upward) the ligaments of the joint are kept stretched, which guarantees the stability of the joint; but with the foot plantarflexed (as when standing on the toes) the narrower width of the trochlea causes the stability to decrease. Behind the trochlea is a posterior process with a medial and a lateral tubercle separated by a groove for the tendon of the flexor hallucis longus. Exceptionally, the lateral of these tubercles forms an independent bone called os trigonum or accessory talus; it may represent the tarsale proximale intermedium. On the bone's inferior side, three articular surfaces serve for the articulation with the calcaneus, and several variously developed articular surfaces exist for the articulation with ligaments.
trgt_first: The body features several prominent articulate surfaces: On its superior side is the trochlea tali, which is semi-cylindrical, and it is flanked by the articulate facets for the two malleoli. The ankle mortise, the fork-like structure of the malleoli, holds these three articulate surfaces in a steady grip, which guarantees the stability of the ankle joint.
mgt: The trochlea tali is narrower at the front than at the back, providing varying stability depending on the foot position. During dorsiflexion, the ligaments tighten, enhancing stability, while plantarflexion allows for more movement but reduces stability. Behind the trochlea lies the sustentaculum tali, and between the medial and lateral tubercles is the intertubercular sulcus, which may form an independent bone called the peroneal tubercle. The three articular surfaces on the inferior side are the anterior, middle, and posterior facets, facilitating complex movements and distributing load effectively.

trgt: For example, in the early stages of the “transgenic mouse revolution”, he and his Hopkins colleague published a comprehensive series of studies detailing the effects on nitric oxide (NO), at the time a novel neural modulator, on behavior. They established a large increase in aggressive behavior and excessive, inappropriate sexual behavior in transgenic mice lacking the NOS gene, which suggested that NO normally forms a behavioral 'brake' on impulsive, motivated behaviors. The functional significance of gaseous neuromodulators was established by this research. This original study was the first comprehensive behavioral phenotyping study in a transgenic mouse. It has been cited over 800 times and provoked much basic research into the biological bases underlying aggression.
trgt_first: At Johns Hopkins, Nelson formed important collaborations with Solomon Snyder among others in the burgeoning field of understanding the behavioral role of specific gene products. He had a role in identifying genes involved in the regulation of motivated behaviors such as aggression and reproduction.
mgt: At Ohio State University, Nelson and his colleagues, including Gregory Demas, Peng Huang, Jacob Bumgarner, William Walker, and Courtney DeVries, conducted pioneering research on the behavioral role of nitric oxide. Their study, published in Nature in 1995, focused on male mice lacking the neuronal nitric oxide synthase (nNOS) gene, revealing significant behavioral abnormalities. This research highlighted the critical role of nitric oxide in various behaviors, suggesting its involvement in modulating physiological and cognitive processes. The study, which utilized comprehensive behavioral phenotyping, was highly influential, with over 1,000 citations to date, underscoring the significance of gaseous neuromodulators in behavior.

trgt: The scholars who studied these remains suggest that, if the disease did migrate from Africa to India during the third millennium BCE, "at a time when there was substantial interaction among the Indus Civilization, Mesopotamia, and Egypt, there needs to be additional skeletal and molecular evidence of leprosy in India and Africa so as to confirm the African origin of the disease." Evidence for the disease was later confirmed in the human skeletal remains from the archaeological site of Harappa, in Pakistan. The disease was thus present in the urban centers of the Indus civilization before 2000 BCE, further supporting the hypothesis it migrated here as part of the "third millennium BCE interaction sphere" – an exchange network that spanned the Arabian Sea.
trgt_first: In 2009 skeletal remains from the second millennium BCE were discovered at Balathal, in Rajasthan, northwest India. Study and analysis of these remains were documented as the oldest skeletal evidence for leprosy.
mgt: In 2009, skeletal remains from the second millennium BCE were discovered at Balathal, in Rajasthan, northwest India. These findings, along with evidence from Harappa and other sites, suggest that leprosy may have migrated from Africa to India during the third millennium BCE, when there was substantial interaction among the Indus Civilization, Mesopotamia, and Egypt. Genetic analysis supports the hypothesis that the disease's African origin can be confirmed through additional skeletal and molecular evidence. Later, the disease was confirmed in human skeletal remains from 300-400 BCE in Egypt and Thailand. The archaeological site of Harappa, located in Pakistan, provides evidence that leprosy was present in the urban centers of the Indus civilization by 2000 BCE, supporting the hypothesis that the disease was transmitted during the third millennium BCE interaction sphere, known as the "Anatolian Trade Network."

In Brooklyn, the E train operates as an express service along the Broadway-Bowery line, running express between Jay Street and Jamaica. The E train provides a critical connection between Downtown Brooklyn and Manhattan, with service extending to Jamaica Center–Parsons/Archer and Canarsie. Despite its importance, the E train has faced challenges due to high ridership and limited capacity. Changes in Brooklyn service, particularly at 179th Street, have been aimed at addressing these issues. In October 1969, the New York City Transit Authority (NYCTA) conducted a test to evaluate the impact of increasing the scheduled frequency of the E and F services along the Queens Boulevard Line in the southbound direction during the morning peak hour. The test involved scheduling 35 trains to leave 179th Street, with 17 E trains and 18 F trains. However, only 32 trains actually left the terminal, 15 E trains and 17 F trains. The study found that the average number of trains actually in service was 28 at Queens Plaza, with 14 Es and 14 Fs, and 31 at 71st Avenue, with 15 Es and 16 Fs. Running such a high frequency of service was not possible without increasing running times and causing congestion. This underscores the need for careful planning and adjustments to maintain efficient service while managing congestion and rider demand.

trgt: Although the determination of psilocin levels in urine can be performed without sample clean-up (i.e., removing potential contaminants that make it difficult to accurately assess concentration), the analysis in plasma or serum requires a preliminary extraction, followed by derivatization of the extracts in the case of GC–MS. A specific immunoassay has also been developed to detect psilocin in whole blood samples. A 2009 publication reported using HPLC to quickly separate forensically important illicit drugs including psilocybin and psilocin, which were identifiable within about half a minute of analysis time. These analytical techniques to determine psilocybin concentrations in body fluids are, however, not routinely available, and not typically used in clinical settings.
trgt_first: Various chromatographic methods have been developed to detect psilocin in body fluids: the rapid emergency drug identification system (REMEDi HS), a drug screening method based on HPLC; HPLC with electrochemical detection; GC–MS; and liquid chromatography coupled to mass spectrometry.
mgt: For the determination of psilocin levels in urine, enzymatic cleavage with β-glucuronidase is required to measure both free and total amounts. Analysis in plasma or serum requires extraction followed by derivatization for GC–MS. Psilocin can be identified within minutes using HPLC. A specific immunoassay using radioimmunoassay (RIA) has been developed for whole blood samples, requiring minimal sample preparation. The REMEDI HS system, based on HPLC, was first described in 1997 and can rapidly separate a wide range of drugs, including psilocybin and psilocin, demonstrating their presence within 30 minutes. These techniques are increasingly utilized in forensic and clinical settings for accurate and efficient psilocybin concentration determination.

Formation:
Seaborne Freight's plans for a Ramsgate-Ostend ferry service were first reported in the Belgian media in early 2018, linking the initiative directly to Brexit concerns. The company had been in discussions with Thanet council since 2017, with the initial target start date being March 2018, but no ferry was in sight. The connection to Brexit was particularly evident given the UK's impending exit from the EU, which raised questions about the resilience of existing ferry services. At this time, Thanet council was led by Chris Wells, a UKIP member, who had been a vocal supporter of Brexit. Despite the initial optimism, the project faced numerous delays and challenges, with Seaborne Freight struggling to meet the necessary criteria to secure the contract.

trgt: Local erosion continued into the Cenozoic era. There is no local rock record for the entirety of the Tertiary. During the more recent Quaternary, New Hampshire was largely covered by glaciers. The local plant life resembled that of modern arctic Canada. This is supported by fossil plants and pollen preserved in sediments deposited when the glaciers melted. Large megafauna roamed the area during interglacial periods, such as woolly mammoths and mastodons.
trgt_first: Erosion continued into the Mesozoic, so the state has almost no rock record from this entire era of geologic time. The few rocks present were igneous and likely formed as a result of the rifting that divided Pangaea. No dinosaur fossils have ever been discovered in New Hampshire. No other fossils are known from this scant rock record either.
mgt: Erosion continued into the Tertiary, leaving a sparse local rock record for this period. New Hampshire was largely covered by glaciers during the Quaternary, with plant life resembling modern arctic Canada due to cooler temperatures. Glaciers retreated after the last Ice Age. Megafauna like mammoths and mastodons roamed during interglacial periods; Shasta ground sloths also inhabited parts of the state.

to advocate a reduction. Gyllenstierna himself was a man of great talent and noble heritage, who has honoured his country and his sex in these our times. Continuation:

In 1680, Charles XI abolished the office of Lord High Chancellor, which Magnus Gabriel De la Gardie had held, and instead established the position of Supreme Chancellor. Coming from a family of prominent military commanders, De la Gardie was no stranger to political and military affairs. In 1674, Gyllenstierna was elevated to the title of count, reflecting his growing influence and importance in the royal court. Gyllenstierna's personal interest lay in strengthening the crown's authority and reducing the power of the nobility and other influential groups, particularly the plutocrats, who he believed were undermining the stability of the kingdom. As a spokesman for the crown, Gyllenstierna advocated for the reduction of the privileges and influence of the plutocrats, aiming to centralize power under the monarch. The author of Les Anecdotes de Suède drew on a variety of sources, including the writings of contemporaries like Maria Gustava Gyllenstierna and historical records from the period, to articulate his concerns about the rise of powerful individuals and the potential threat they posed to the monarchy and the nation's well-being.

mgt: Mental health is another issue faced by many refugee women, significantly impacted by cultural adaptation stress. In the mid-2000s, Hushidar Mortezaie and Michael Sears held a fashion show in New York City that garnered significant attention and controversy. During this show, models walked the runway dressed in traditional Iranian chadors and holding machine guns, a striking juxtaposition that was intended to challenge prevailing stereotypes. However, the media misinterpreted the event, leading to widespread reports that the show featured actual weapons and models in chadors. This misunderstanding sparked outrage and criticism from various quarters, including human rights organizations and religious leaders. In response to the misunderstanding, Hushidar Mortezaie clarified that the show was a commentary on media sensationalism and cultural stereotypes, emphasizing that there were no real weapons or chadors as initially reported. Instead, the work aimed to subvert the very narratives that had led to such misinterpretations, highlighting the complexity of cultural representation in contemporary fashion.

trgt: The ECL was also expensive for users to run because the gate drain current produced so much heat that the CPU had to packaged into a special module called a Thermal Conduction Module (TCM) that had inert gas pistons and needed plumbed to be high-volume chilled water to be cooled. But the air-cooled CMOS technology's CPU speed initially was much slower than the ECL (notably the boxes available from the mainframe-clone makers Amdahl and Hitachi). This was especially concerning to IBM in the CICS context as almost all the largest mainframe customers were running CICS and for many of them it was the primary mainframe workload.
trgt_first: The Sysplex was to be based on CMOS (Complementary Metal Oxide Silicon) rather than the existing ECL (Emitter Coupled Logic) hardware. The cost of scaling the mainframe-unique ECL was much higher than CMOS which was being developed by a keiretsu with high-volume use cases such as Sony PlayStation to reduce the unit cost of each generation's CPUs.
mgt: The Sysplex was to be based on CMOS rather than the existing ECL hardware, as ECL was expensive for users to run due to high power consumption. The CPU was packaged into a Thermal Conduction Module (TCM) to manage heat from the gate drain current. The TCM featured pistons conducting heat to a cooling chamber, requiring chilled water for efficient cooling. Air-cooled CMOS was significantly slower (2x) than ECL, making it less attractive for performance-critical workloads. Companies like Control Data and Motorola provided ECL technology in their systems. The slower speed of CMOS was concerning for IBM, especially given the performance demands of CICS, a primary mainframe workload for large customers.

trgt_first: As an introduced species, the common alder can affect the ecology of its new locality. It is a fast-growing tree and can quickly form dense woods where little light reaches the ground, and this may inhibit the growth of native plants. The presence of the nitrogen-fixing bacteria and the annual accumulation of leaf litter from the trees also alters the nutrient status of the soil.
mgt:
. Its dense root system can trap sediment and alter water flow in wetland ecosystems, which can degrade habitat for other species. The plant can also deoxygenate water and shade out other species. Alnus glutinosa is monoecious and reproduces mainly by seed, with wind being the primary agent of pollination and seed dispersal."

Continuation:

The dense network of roots of Alnus glutinosa can significantly enhance the availability of phosphorus in the soil, making it more accessible to other plants (Giardina et al. 2010). This nutrient enrichment can support a wider variety of plant life in the surrounding area. Additionally, the roots play a crucial role in stabilizing sediments and preventing erosion, particularly in riparian zones and wetlands, which can help maintain the health and structure of aquatic ecosystems. However, the dense root system can also lead to the formation of pure stands or thickets, potentially displacing native species and creating monocultures, especially in disturbed wetland sites (Herron et al. 2007, Eckel 2003, NatureServe 2010).

Alnus glutinosa primarily spreads its seeds through wind-dispersed catkins, which contain numerous small, winged nutlets. While birds do contribute to seed dispersal, their role is secondary compared to wind (USDA Forest Service 2006). After detaching from the parent tree, the woody fruits of Alnus glutinosa remain viable for extended periods, allowing for continued dispersal over time. When the tree is felled, the stumps often resprout vigorously, necessitating follow-up treatments with herbicides to prevent regrowth (Claessens et al. 2010; Funk 2005). In the Midwestern United States, specifically in Indiana, Alnus glutinosa is considered a highly invasive terrestrial plant and is prohibited (NatureServe 2010). In New Zealand, the species is classified as an environmental weed, indicating its potential to cause ecological harm through its invasive nature (NatureServe 2010).

Lancet windows are flanked by Ionic columns on the first floor, while the ground floor is decorated with ornate ironwork and ceramic tiles. The elevation features detailed stonework and a mansard roof covering both building wings. Inside, the main staircase is adorned with a wrought-iron balustrade embellished with scrolling foliage and floral motifs. The main hall is ornamented with frescoes depicting historical scenes, and the second-floor auditorium is garnished with a coffered ceiling and stained glass windows.

trgt: The pines could have been planted at any time between the 1870s and 1920s, probably as part of a Melton Shire town beautification policy. They are the same as those that survive on Gap Road and several of the streets of Sunbury that were once a part of Melton Shire. (Maybe they served to mark Melton’s fragile proprietorship in the area.) In Victoria conifer plantings had been recommended for street planting in the 1860s, but from the 1880s they were often replaced by deciduous trees, and the Monterey Pines at Aitkens Gap are one of only a few stands of old conifer street plantings which remain in Victoria.
trgt_first: As the Bendigo railway beyond Sunbury opened in stages from 1859, The Gap’s fortunes declined dramatically. It struggled on as a town serving a local farming community. A Church of England school opened at the settlement in 1857, and a state school continued until 1900. In the 1990s no relic could be found of the Caroline Chisholm shelter shed that had been erected at the Gap during the gold rush. The one surviving row of the avenue of old Monterey Pines (Pinus radiata) on the Calder Highway is today the most prominent evidence of the former township.
mgt: As the Bendigo railway beyond Sunbury opened in stages from 1859, The Gap’s fortunes declined dramatically. It struggled on as a town serving a local farming community. A Church of England school opened at the settlement in 1857, and a state school continued until 1900. In the 1990s no relic could be found of the Caroline Chisholm shelter shed that had been erected at the Gap during the gold rush. The one surviving row of the avenue of old Monterey Pines (Pinus radiata) on the Calder Highway is today the most prominent evidence of the former township. These pines, likely planted in the late 19th century, were part of broader conifer plantings recommended for street planting in Victoria from the 1850s. By the 1920s, conifer plantings began to be replaced by deciduous trees. Notably, similar Monterey Pines can be found in Melton Shire, reflecting the historical relationship between Sunbury and Melton's shared agricultural and forestry heritage.

trgt: The scholar Daniel Stokl Ben Ezra suggests that the eve of Yom Kippur coincided with 20 September, i.e. with the last day of the week of Christian celebration called the "Encaenia" (dedication of the church of the Holy Sepulchre, which celebration was connected to the discovering of the True Cross). Actually the central idea of John's homily is linked to the celebration of Kippur: 109 , through the blessing of the church altar, symbolized by the "Kaporet" (Mercy seat).
trgt_first: The new building on Mount Zion left untouched the Judeo-Christian synagogue. The day of the consecration was, according to van Esbrœck, 15 September 394, and van Esbrœck suggests that it very probably corresponded in such a year to the 10th of Tishrei,: 112 the traditional day of the Hebraic holiday of Yom Kippur.
mgt: According to Daniel Stokl Ben Ezra, the eve of Yom Kippur coincided with 20 September in 394. This date aligns with the Christian celebration of the Encaenia, dedicated to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre. The Encaenia marks the dedication of the church, paralleling the Jewish Yom Kippur. In John’s homily, the blessing of the church altar symbolizes the transition of believers into the Kingdom of God, echoing the concept of atonement and renewal, similar to the Kaporet’s role in covering and atoning for sins.

trgt: Osamu Shirota and colleagues reported a method for the large-scale synthesis of psilocybin without chromatographic purification in 2003. Starting with 4-hydroxyindole, they generated psilocybin from psilocin in 85% yield, a marked improvement over yields reported from previous syntheses. Purified psilocybin is a white, crystalline powder. There are two known crystalline polymorphs of psilocybin, as well as reported hydrated phases. The compound is reported to have a melting point between 220–228 °C (428–442 °F), and a slightly ammonia-like taste. In 2020, a second-generation synthesis of psilocybin has been developed.
trgt_first: Psilocybin is an alkaloid that is soluble in water, methanol and aqueous ethanol, but insoluble in organic solvents like chloroform and petroleum ether. : 15 Its pKa values are estimated to be 1.3 and 6.5 for the two successive phosphate OH groups and 10.4 for the dimethylamine nitrogen, so in general it exists as a zwitterionic structure. Exposure to light is detrimental to the stability of aqueous solutions of psilocybin, and will cause it to rapidly oxidize—an important consideration when using it as an analytical standard.
mgt: In 2003, Osamu Shirota and colleagues reported a method for the large-scale synthesis of psilocybin without chromatographic purification, using psilocin as the starting material, achieving a yield of 78%. Purified psilocybin appears as white needles or powder. There are currently five known crystalline polymorphs of psilocybin, with reported melting points ranging from 228 to 231°C. Psilocybin is tasteless. A second-generation synthesis was developed in 2011.

trgt: He suggests there are differences between PCL-R-diagnosed psychopaths and non-psychopaths on "processing and use of linguistic and emotional information", while such differences are potentially smaller between those diagnosed with ASPD and without. Additionally, Hare argued confusion regarding how to diagnose ASPD, confusion regarding the difference between ASPD and psychopathy, as well as the differing future prognoses regarding recidivism and treatability, may have serious consequences in settings such as court cases where psychopathy is often seen as aggravating the crime.
trgt_first: Although the diagnosis of ASPD covers two to three times as many prisoners than the diagnosis of psychopathy, Robert Hare believes the PCL-R is better able to predict future criminality, violence, and recidivism than a diagnosis of ASPD.
mgt: Robert Hare suggests that PCL-R-diagnosed psychopaths exhibit significant differences in interpersonal and affective traits compared to non-psychopaths. These differences are most pronounced in experiments focusing on linguistic and emotional material. In contrast, individuals with ASPD show little distinction from those without ASPD in such tests. Hare argues that confusion between ASPD and psychopathy can lead to misdiagnosis and inappropriate treatment, potentially exacerbating recidivism. He also notes that psychopathy is often viewed as an aggravating factor in criminal behavior.

trgt: In the early 20th century, rebuking alleged "health faddists" like Kellogg and Sylvester Graham, American physicians who embraced focal infection theory cast themselves in the German tradition of "scientific medicine". Kellogg argued that German researchers ostensibly repudiated the autointoxication principle, but, by using different terminology, supported it circuitously. Since French pathologist Charles Jacques Bouchard, in his 1887 book, coined the term autointoxication, French researchers had investigated and openly advocated the principle, already presaged by multiple researchers in Europe and America. Meanwhile, British surgeons still knife-happy, Hunter warned of "intestinal stasis" impairing mental stability, and called for "surgical bacteriology".
trgt_first: Since 1875, American medical doctor John Harvey Kellogg in Battle Creek, Michigan, at his huge sanitarium—advertised as "University of Health", staffing some 800 to 1 000, and yearly receiving several thousand patients, including US Presidents and celebrities—had battled degeneration and disease by fending off bowel sepsis.

trgt: While some states have their own preventive detention acts, there are four central acts covering preventive detention at a national level: the National Security Act (NSA) of 1980, the Conservation of Foreign Exchange and Prevention of Smuggling Activities Act (COFEPOSA) of 1974, the Prevention of Black Marketing & Maintenance of Supplies of Essential Commodities Act of 1980, and the Prevention of Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances Act, 1988. The time duration of detention permitted under these acts varies from 24 hours to over a year.
page_title: Jammu and Kashmir Public Safety Act, 1978
trgt_first: Currently the provision for preventive detention in India exists under the Code of Criminal Procedure, which draws its roots from laws in British India. The Jammu and Kashmir Public Safety Act of 1978 is only one of the acts in India that cater to prevention detention at a state level.
mgt: Currently, the provision for preventive detention in India exists under several central acts, including the National Security Act, 1980, the Foreign Exchange Management Act, 1974, the Maharashtra Prevention of Cruelty to Animals Act, 1980, and the Prevention of Black Marketing and Supply of Essential Commodities Act, 1980. The Civil Liberties Act of 1988 addresses past detentions. Minimum detention is typically 24 hours, while maximum can extend to over a year. States like Maharashtra have their own preventive detention acts.

trgt: River-names (Hydronyms) such as Deva, Deua or Deba (Goddess) were also of Indo-European etymology. As with the Caristii, not a single toponym related to the Aquitanian-Basque languages has been found, further proving the theory of their Celtic origin and possible late Basquisation. However, but for a few exceptions (Deba, Zegama, Arakama) present-day place-names show a clear prevalence of the Basque linguistic element (sometimes mixed with Latin and Romance lexical roots).
trgt_first: As with the Caristii, it is discussed whether the Varduli were an Aquitanian tribe or a Celt one, related to the Cantabri and Celtiberians. Their place-names (Toponyms) were clearly of Indo-European origin (probably Proto-Celtic language), as Uxama (comes from Upsama, meaning "the highest"), Deobriga (comes from Deiuo-Briga, meaning "holy hill"), Tullonium (comes from Tullo, meaning "valley"), among others.
mgt:
The Linguistic and Cultural Evolution of the Basque Region":

The linguistic and cultural evolution of the Basque region is complex and intertwined with various influences, including Celtic, Aquitanian, and later Latin and Romance languages. Despite the absence of complete inscriptions in their native language, personal names recorded in Latin inscriptions provide valuable insights into the Aquitanian language, which is considered the precursor to modern Basque. The Roman records indicate that the lands of Irun, known as Oiasso, belonged to the Vascon tribe rather than the Varduli, suggesting a distinct tribal identity within the region. The Old English place-names, rich in semantic parallels with indigenous names worldwide, offer a unique perspective on traditional ecological knowledge (TEK). The extension of the current western Basque dialects aligns with the historical territories of the tribes described by Greco-Roman geographers, leading some linguists to propose that each tribe might have had its own dialect or that they spoke a language closely related to modern Basque. The presence of Celtic toponyms, particularly in the southern regions, further complicates the linguistic landscape, indicating a gradual Basquisation process among the tribes, likely influenced by the advancing Aquitanian tribes. The term 'Varduli' is of Celtic origin, possibly meaning 'borderland,' and is reflected in the modern Basque name 'Guipuzcoa,' which similarly conveys a sense of border or limit. This linguistic evolution reflects the dynamic cultural and ethnic interactions that shaped the region over millennia.

trgt: Van Dyke later said that the team never wanted to abandon the pixel art style of the previous games, declaring that it was "part of the DNA". The layout of levels was compared by van den Berg to a panorama: Both he and van Dyke said it was challenging to create mechanics that allow for player strategy while also sticking to a "one-dimensional" design; van den Berg paid specifically paid attention to forcing units to "overlap" and take the same place in a single dimension. Some weapons, such as the area of effect catapult, could take advantage of the overlap in order to hit multiple targets at once. Van den Berg felt as these elements made the game's mechanics "much less predictable".
trgt_first: The pixel art style was intended primarily to cut time between drawing and implementing the designs in gameplay: van den Berg found it relatively easy to create, saying that only finding the right font and designing a "rotating style" caused some issues. Although van den Berg was inspired somewhat by retro games, he liked pixel art primarily for its impressionism and that it allowed for the viewer to interpret its details for themselves.
mgt: Van Dyke emphasized that the team never wanted to abandon the strategic depth and replayability from previous games, declaring that these were 'part of the DNA.' Van den Berg compared the level layout to a panning mechanism, allowing for a focus on strategy without hindering movement. Both faced challenges in balancing the mechanics, particularly in avoiding weapon overlap. They aimed to stick to a base sword and gun design, with van den Berg paying special attention to the distinct hitboxes for different weapons. This design allowed for niche uses of side weapons, enhancing the game's complexity and appeal.

trgt: He writes that the reptilian features of the skull are much more pronounced, citing features of the teeth, fenestrae, and jaw structure as being undeniably un-birdlike. Heilmann found that much of Archaeopteryx's anatomy, in fact, was decidedly reptilian and generally opposed to that of modern birds. This included the pelvis, which lacks a pectineal process and has a very different os sacrum from modern birds, as well as the carpus, which Heilmann wrote exhibited the same phenomena found in the wrists of modern reptiles. Its tail was also noted by Heilmann as being extremely reptilian and resembling nothing known of modern birds.
trgt_first: Early in this section Heilmann embarks on a thorough description of the Berlin Archaeopteryx specimen, which includes detailed comparisons to specific aspects of modern birds. Following a comparison of its skull to that of Aetosaurus, Euparkeria, and a modern pigeon, Heilmann states that he disagrees with the scientific consensus of the time that the skull of Archaeopteryx is that of a true bird.
mgt: Early in this section Heilmann embarks on a thorough description of the Berlin Archaeopteryx specimen, which includes detailed comparisons to specific aspects of modern birds. Following a comparison of its skull to that of Aetosaurus, Euparkeria, and a modern pigeon, Heilmann states that he disagrees with the scientific consensus of the time that the skull of Archaeopteryx is that of a true bird. Heilmann cited the absence of a pectineal process, the structure of the os sacrum, and the carpus as undeniably un-birdlike features. He found that Archaeopteryx's hindlimbs lacked the necessary arrangement for aerodynamic functions, and the tail was more akin to that of reptiles than modern birds.

trgt: At the center of a level plateau, it is approximately equal to the free air anomaly. Models such as deep dynamic isostasy (DDI) include such viscous forces and are applicable to a dynamic mantle and lithosphere. Measurements of the rate of isostatic rebound (the return to isostatic equilibrium following a change in crust loading) provide information on the viscosity of the upper mantle.
trgt_first: Perfect isostatic equilibrium is possible only if mantle material is in rest. However, thermal convection is present in the mantle. This introduces viscous forces that are not accounted for the static theory of isostacy. The isostatic anomaly or IA is defined as the Bouger anomaly minus the gravity anomaly due to the subsurface compensation, and is a measure of the local departure from isostatic equilibrium.
mgt: At the center of a level plateau, the isostatic anomaly is approximately equal to the free air anomaly. Deep dynamic isostasy (DDI) models include viscous forces and are applicable to a dynamic mantle and lithosphere. Measurements of the rate of isostatic rebound provide information on the viscosity of the upper mantle, reflecting changes in crust loading and their impact on isostatic equilibrium.

trgt: Removal of anemones at rates higher than their resettlement into the reefs, as observed in the Philippines, is known to have caused drastic reduction in the localised population of clownfish or anemonefish (Amphiprion sp.). Evolutionarily, anemone fish observed on reefs that were subjected to intense and prolonged anemone fishing were significantly smaller, even for mature adult pairs, than those found living with an anemone. This size reduction is attributed to their need to hide in small coral crevices in the absence of a host.
trgt_first: Another example of FIE that is instigated indirectly can be seen in the ornamental or aquarium trade industry. In particular, corals and anemones are highly prized ornamental commodities and are often harvested at unsustainable rates for profit within the Malay archipelago.
mgt: In the Philippines, intense anemone fishing has led to a drastic reduction in clownfish (scientific name: Amphiprioninae) populations. On affected reefs, mature adult pairs were smaller compared to those living with an anemone, likely due to the necessity of hiding in small coral crevices to avoid predators in an anemone-free environment. This behavior emerged as a survival strategy in response to the altered habitat caused by anemone removal, which occurred at higher rates than their resettlement.

The main burner of the temple was moved outside to minimise smoke damage and the sunken floor area which housed it has been filled in by the addition of removable timber panels. The temple reopened around Chinese New Year in 1998–99. Around that time, the associated terrace houses were refurbished, improving living conditions for the elderly residents.
trgt_first: In 1995–96, conservation documentation of both the temple and Retreat Street was completed. A fire broke out in the temple in December 1996, but was quickly extinguished. In 1997–98, the building and associated objects were restored and cleaned in conjunction with community artisans and architects as well as Powerhouse Museum staff, informed by the earlier conservation documentation. The temple roof was replicated using imported Chinese tiles. Damaged timber panels from the temple interior were restored. Undamaged wooden items were cleaned.

trgt: The formation of the Himalayan mountains and the Qinghai–Tibetan Plateau for example have driven the speciation and diversification of numerous plants and animals such as Lepisorus ferns; glyptosternoid fishes (Sisoridae); and the Rana chensinensis species complex. Uplift has also driven vicariant speciation in Macowania daisies in South Africa's Drakensberg mountains, along with Dendrocincla woodcreepers in the South American Andes. The Laramide orogeny during the Late Cretaceous even caused vicariant speciation and radiations of dinosaurs in North America.
trgt_first: Patterns of increased endemism at higher elevations on both islands and continents have been documented on a global level. As topographical elevation increases, species become isolated from one another; often constricted to graded zones. This isolation on "mountain top islands" creates barriers to gene flow, encouraging allopatric speciation, and generating the formation of endemic species. Mountain building (orogeny) is directly correlated with—and directly affects biodiversity.
mgt: Patterns of increased endemism at higher elevations have been documented globally. Geological formations like the Himalayan mountains and the Qinghai–Tibetan Plateau have driven the speciation and diversification of numerous plants and animals, including Lepisorus ferns, which experienced allopatric speciation due to the uplift of the Himalayas. In South Africa, the Drakensberg mountains have affected Macowania daisies, causing vicariant speciation. In the South American Andes, Dendrocincla woodcreepers exhibit allopatric speciation. During the Late Cretaceous, orogenic episodes in the Western Interior Basin led to vicariant speciation and radiations of North American dinosaurs.

mgt: , the town was home to over 1,000 Chinese traders. The goods are then sold to Angolan traders, who use them to supply their own local markets. Additionally, some Chinese businesspeople have set up factories in Oshikango, primarily for manufacturing goods for export to Angola. mgt:
case Julia Gould Hall v. The Bark 'Emily Banning' have in the context of maritime law?

---

Life and career

Julia Gould, born in Sydney, Australia, in 1865, was a pioneering nurse who dedicated much of her life to the improvement of healthcare standards. She served as the third matron of the Royal Prince Alfred Hospital in Sydney and played a crucial role in founding the Australian Trained Nurses Association in 1899, which later evolved into the Australian Nursing Federation. In 1914, Gould embarked on a journey to the Middle East as part of the AIF contingent, where she was commissioned to set up the Australian General Hospital (2AGH) in Cairo. During her voyage, she was on the Euripides, a troop transport ship, when it was briefly taken over by the crew of the Emily Banning. Unfortunately, Gould’s trunk, containing all her personal belongings, was lost during this incident. In an attempt to recover the value of her lost items, Gould initiated a legal action against the bark Emily Banning. The case, Julia Gould Hall v. The Bark 'Emily Banning', reached the Supreme Court of California in 1915 and had significant implications for maritime law.

trgt: Two scenes could be exhibited at the rotunda in Leicester Square simultaneously, however the rotunda at Leicester Square was the only rotunda to house two panoramas. Houses with single scenes proved more popular. While at Leicester Square, the audience was herded down a long, dark corridor to clear their minds. The idea was to have spectators more or less forget what they just saw, leaving their minds blank to view the second scene. Despite the audience's "mind blanking" walk in the dark, panoramas were designed to have a lingering effect upon the viewer. For some, this attribute placed panoramas in the same category as propaganda of the period: no more than an illusion meant to deceive.
trgt_first: The main goal of the panorama was to immerse the audience to the point where they could not tell the difference between the canvas and reality, in other words, wholeness. To accomplish this, all borders of the canvas had to be concealed. Props were also strategically positioned in the foreground of the scene to increase realism. Two windows laid into the roof allowed natural light to flood the canvases, also making the illusion more realistic.

trgt: The island lacks predators and other competitors, and as such can be expected to be at full carrying capacity for rails. This in turn would favour energy conservation by the rails, resulting in small body size, low BMR and flightlessness. A comparison of flighted and flightless rails, including the Inaccessible Island rail, found that rails that lose the ability to fly also have low BMRs.
trgt_first: The Inaccessible Island rail has a low basal metabolic rate (BMR), measured in 1989 at around 60–68% the rate expected for a bird of its weight. The scientists responsible for the study speculated that the low BMR was not as a result of flightlessness, which does not have this effect in other bird species, but was instead the result of the rail's island lifestyle.
mgt: The Inaccessible Island rail has a low BMR, estimated at 60–68% of expected values, likely due to its island lifestyle with minimal predator and competitor pressure. This low BMR supports a larger body size and flightlessness, favored by the island’s full carrying capacity. Comparing flightless weka to flighted rails showed that flightless rails can drastically reduce energy requirements. Thus, flight loss is an adaptive strategy for survival on isolated islands.

trgt_first: A burning or gnawing feeling in the stomach area lasting between 30 minutes and 3 hours commonly accompanies ulcers. This pain can be misinterpreted as hunger, indigestion, or heartburn. mgt: A burning or gnawing feeling in the stomach area lasting between 30 minutes and 3 hours commonly accompanies ulcers. Pain may be temporarily relieved by eating certain foods or taking acid-reducing medications like antacids. However, symptoms vary among individuals; some find relief after eating, while others experience pain that is worse after meals.

trgt_first: In December 2014, IS recruiters in Turkey told their Libyan associates to stop sending fighters to Syria and to focus on domestic attacks, according to the Wall Street Journal. In the following weeks, IS carried out attacks against oil installations and international hotels, performed mass executions and attempted to take over further Libyan territory.
mgt: In December 2014, IS recruiters in Turkey told their Libyan associates to stop sending fighters to Syria. Instead, IS made tactical alliances with Ansar al-Sharia Libya, particularly its Benghazi branch, and with Ansar al-Sharia from Tunisia. It also allied with the Khorasen Brigade of AQIM. Abu Abdullah Al-Libi, Ansar al-Sharia's top religious scholar, pledged allegiance to IS on March 19, 2015, taking a cadre of fighters with him. Following this, several prominent Ansar al-Sharia members, including Abu Abdullah's replacement, Abu Tamim al-Libi, defected to IS.

trgt_first: William C. W. Mow was born on 18 April 1936 in Hangzhou, China. After graduating from Riverdale Country School in 1955, he earned a BSEE from Rensselaer Polytechnic, MSEE from Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn and a PhD degree in Electrical Engineering from Purdue University in 1967. He became famous as the founder and CEO of Bugle Boy Industries, a clothing company especially known for its brand of denim jeans.
mgt: William C. W. Mow was born on 18 April 1936 in Hangzhou, China. After graduating from Riverdale Country School in 1955, he earned advanced degrees and founded Bugle Boy Industries, which achieved significant sales and industry status in the 1980s. However, by the late '90s, Bugle Boy struggled and declared bankruptcy in 2001. William donated part of his fortune to Riverdale Country School in 1953, where his son attended and the main building on Hill Campus is named after Thomas I. Gasson, SJ.

trgt: In September 2017, Conti injured his anterior cruciate ligament for the first time, and in March 2018 suffered a recurrence of the injury, effectively ending his season. The club ruled out the possibility of any further emergency signings, thus trusting Calabria as a long-term replacement for Conti in the right full-back position. He completed the season with 30 appearances in all competitions and scored his debut goal in senior professional football on 25 February 2018 in the Serie A 2–0 away win against Roma.
trgt_first: Ahead of the 2017–18 season, Milan acquired Atalanta's Andrea Conti for nearly €25 million, viewing the player as the most likely starter on the right side of the team's defensive line; Calabria had been persuaded yet refused to join one of the lower-ranking Serie A teams on loan to increase his playing time.
mgt: Andrea Conti first injured his anterior cruciate ligament in September 2017, effectively ending his debut season at AC Milan. The recurrence of his anterior cruciate ligament injury occurred in October 2021, leading to further knee surgery and sidelining him for an extended period. In response to Conti's injury recurrence, AC Milan did not pursue emergency signings but instead trusted Hans Hateboer as a long-term replacement for Conti in the right full-back position. During the 2017–18 season, Davide Calabria made 30 appearances in all competitions, including his first senior goal, which came on February 25, 2018, against Roma at the Stadio Olimpico. This goal sealed the victory for AC Milan, who won 2-0, with Calabria's goal being the second of the match following Patrick Cutrone's opener. Calabria also scored his first goal in a Serie A match, celebrating after scoring his team's first goal during the Serie A match between Atalanta Bc and AC Milan on October 3, 2021.

trgt_first: In Treblinka, Lajcher was put in charge of a small infirmary for the SS after the suicide of his predecessor, Dr. Julian Chorążycki (not to be mistaken with the "fake" infirmary called "lazaret" where the hands-on killing took place). Asked by the Underground, according to Samuel Rajzman, he also agreed to take the leadership in their secret escape plan.
mgt: In Treblinka, Lajcher managed the SS infirmary after Dr. Julian Chorążycki's suicide. Zelomir Bloch led the Organizing Committee at Treblinka Totenlager, while Chorążycki oversaw the sick bay. The uprising was planned for April 21, 1943, when many Germans and Ukrainians were absent swimming in the Bug River. Ambushed by Kurt Franz, Chorążycki attacked Franz with a knife. The revolt was launched by prisoners on July 22, 1943.

mgt: Matthew Bulger notes that the creators are trying to communicate a message about focusing on human relationships rather than getting lost in existential despair. Eric Armstrong of The New Republic observes that Morty represents a hopeful, naive character who, despite discovering bleak truths, remains resilient and focused on his relationships.
